<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch11-relativistic" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Special Relativistic Quantum Mechanics (Dimension 2)</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>Dimension two asks: what spacetime symmetries govern the system? Non-relativistic quantum mechanics assumes Galilean invariance. Lorentz invariance requires a fundamental transformation: the Dirac equation replaces the Schrödinger equation, antiparticles emerge necessarily, and the Hilbert space must accommodate creation and annihilation of particles. This chapter develops special relativistic quantum mechanics, culminating in Quantum Electrodynamics (QED).</p>
  </introduction>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch11-dirac">
    <title>The Dirac Equation</title>
    <p>The Dirac equation is</p>
    <me>
      (i\gamma^\mu \partial_\mu - m)\psi = 0,
    </me>
    <p>where <m>\gamma^\mu</m> are Dirac matrices and <m>\psi</m> is a four-component spinor. It automatically incorporates spin-1/2 and predicts antimatter: every solution has a partner with opposite charge and energy. The equation is linear in time, preserving quantum structure while respecting Lorentz invariance.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch11-solutions">
    <title>Plane Wave Solutions and Antiparticles</title>
    <p>Solutions have the form <m>\psi \sim e^{i(p \cdot x - Et)/\hbar}</m>. Remarkably, negative-energy solutions exist. Dirac's interpretation: these are positive-energy antiparticles with reversed quantum numbers. Hole theory—later unified with the field-theoretic viewpoint—predicts the positron, found experimentally in 1932.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch11-field-quantization">
    <title>Quantizing the Dirac Field</title>
    <p>Treating <m>\psi</m> as a field to be quantized, with anticommutation relations for fermions, naturally gives creation and annihilation operators for particles and antiparticles. This is Quantum Field Theory, where particles are excitations of underlying quantum fields.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch11-summary">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>The Dirac equation is the relativistic generalization of the Schrödinger equation for spin-1/2 particles.</li>
      <li>Lorentz invariance necessitates both positive and negative energy solutions.</li>
      <li>Antimatter emerges naturally from relativistic quantum mechanics.</li>
      <li>Quantizing relativistic fields leads to particle creation and annihilation.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</chapter>
